To generate synthetic data for laser-accelerated ion beams using MATLAB, you can use a random number generator to create values for each feature based on their respective distributions. For example, you could use the following code snippet to randomly generate target material values within the specified bounds:

```matlab
function new_data = generate_target(num_samples)

% specify the bounds for the target material variable
upper_bound_material = 0.25;
lower_bound_material = 0;
rand_gen = randi([lower_bound_material lower_bound_material], upper_bound_material, 'Distribution', 'Uniform');

% generate values within the specified bounds for each target material data point
for i = 1:num_samples
    % calculate the new values
    new_data(i,:) = zeros(length(new_data));
    new_data(i,:) = rand([lower_bound_material lower_bound_material], upper_bound_material, ...
        'Distribution', 'Uniform');
end
```

You can generate pulse width values using the same approach as for the other features. For example:

```matlab
function new_data = generate_pulse_width(num_samples)
% specify the bounds for the pulse width
upper_bound_pulse_width = 0.25;
lower_bound_pulse_width = 0;
rand_gen = randi([lower_bound_pulse_width lower_bound_pulse_width], upper_bound_pulse_width, 'Distribution', ...
% generate values within the specified bounds for each pulse width data point
for i = 1:num_samples
    new_data(i,:) = zeros(length(new_data));
end
% generate energy values using a similar approach as for the other features.
new_data(i,:) = zeros(length(new_data),'Distribution', 'Uniform');
```
